  "prompt": "How does protein catabolism occur?",
  "response": "Protein catabolism is the breakdown of proteins into smaller peptides and amino acids through several key processes:\n\n1. Enzymatic Breakdown\n- Proteases and peptidases cleave protein peptide bonds\n- Occurs in lysosomes, cytosol, and digestive system\n- Breakdown of cellular and dietary proteins\n\n2. Cellular Mechanisms\n- Ubiquitin-proteasome system\n- Autophagy\n- Lysosomal protein degradation\n\n3. Specific Breakdown Pathways\n- Protein deamination\n- Transamination\n- Oxidative deamination\n- Conversion of amino acids to metabolic intermediates\n\n4. Amino Acid Metabolism\n- Amino acids can be:\n- Used for energy production\n- Converted to glucose\n- Used for new protein synthesis\n- Converted to other biomolecules\n\n5. Regulation Factors\n- Nutritional status\n- Hormonal signals\n- Energy requirements\n- Cellular stress\n- Protein damage\n\n6. Key Enzymes Involved\n- Proteasomes\n- Cathepsins\n- Calpains\n- Aminotransferases\n\nThe process ensures protein homeostasis, removes damaged proteins, and provides metabolic flexibility for energy and biosynthetic needs.",
